post_text:
The District is providing school supplies to all students this year free of charge. For families that would like to collect paper/pencil school supplies for Remote Learning, supplies will be distributed on the 17th and 18th of September.

There will be two pickup opportunities at the Astoria School District Transportation Department, located at 35062 Hwy 101 Business:

Drive-up/thru on Thursday, September 17 from 11AM - 6 PM
Drive-up/thru on Friday, September 18, from 8AM - 3 PM

The supplies are together by grade level, based on the supply lists posted to the website at the beginning of a typical year, and each student bag will contain those basic supplies.

This pickup is for paper/pencil school supplies ONLY; Chromebooks will not be available for pickup.

If you have any questions, please email techhelp@astoriak12.org.

post_text:
Astoria School District is gearing up for the beginning of the school year in remote learning. Beginning the week of September 14 teachers will be completing conferences with parents as an entry into remote learning.

As part of students beginning in remote, the District will be using a digital platform called Edgenuity that is designed to communicate and organize lessons for students, staff, and families. In addition, middle and high school students and parents will have access to ParentVue to monitor student grades. During the week of September 14 teachers will be reviewing this information with students and parents.

To help facilitate with login support of the different programs the District will open up Technology Hubs in the gym at Astoria High School and the cafeteria at Astoria Middle School on Wednesday, September 16, and Thursday, September 17 from 1:00 pm to 7:00 pm. Appointments are not necessary, but only a few people will be let in at a time do to social distancing. The District will require people who enter the Technology Hubs at the middle and high school to complete a health questionnaire and facemasks are required. District staff will be sanitizing computers between uses.

If you have any questions please email techhelp@astoriak12.org.

post_text:
Astoria School District will be distributing Chromebooks for K-12 students on September 10 and September 11, 2020. The Chromebooks will be delivered to families that indicated a need on the parent survey, located on the District website.

If your family is in need of a Chromebook and did not complete the parent survey, please email techhelp@astoriak12.org or call the school your child attends.

Important Chromebook Delivery Information:
• District staff will not leave the Chromebook on doorsteps if no one is home.
• District staff will not deliver to households where dogs are unattended or there are no trespassing signs.
• District staff will leave a flyer with contact information if no one is home, or if there are unattended dogs.

If a student has signed up for a Chromebook and has not received a Chromebook on either September 10 or September 11, please email techhelp@astoriak12.org for assistance.

post_text: Congratulations to the AHS FFA team!
shared_text:
Astoria FFA
August 26 at 12:06 PM ·

Astoria FFA virtually attended the Oregon FFA State Horse Evaluation and placed 4th in state. Team members were Alivia Rickenbach, Samantha Davenport ,and Jena Russel. Students who participate in this Career Development Event (CDE) gain new insights into equine science by evaluating and ranking horses based on breed characteristics, conformation and performance. Participants defend their decisions through oral reasons in front of a panel of judges.
In this team CDE, students solve problems related to everything from the nutrition and reproduction of horses to the tack/equipment and feed used to care for horses. Participants strengthen their leadership, observation, analysis, critical thinking and communication skills while also developing and exercising a competitive team spirit and building an awareness of career opportunities within the equine industry. #astoriaffa #gofish #ffa

post_text:
Astoria School District’s Bond projects are well underway. We would like to thank the local contractors, including P&L Johnson Mechanical, Big River Construction and JP Plumbing, who are working within the Astoria School District Bond projects and helping to keep them on schedule and running smoothly. The following is an example of some of the work by local contractors.

At Astor Elementary:
• P&L Johnson Mechanical is installing two new boiler systems, heating, and ventilation systems.
• Big River is excavating the hillside for the new connector, excavating the front of the building for the light well and excavating the new entryway for the multipurpose room.
• JP Plumbing is installing new water heaters, installing plumbing in the new restroom locations, and rerouting plumbing lines for future access.

At Astoria Middle School:

• JP Plumbing safed off all locations at demolition areas for the new building, and they are installing underground plumbing in various locations.
• Big River completed demolition of the diamond building and are preparing the ground for construction of a new facility.
• P&L Johnson safed off mechanical items within the building and are installing the new boiler.

At Astoria High School:

• JP Plumbing safed off all locations impacted by construction, and are also installing new plumbing locations and underground plumbing in various locations throughout the building.
• Big River is preparing the site for construction of the new fine arts building, and are installing new sidewalks around the building.

For current progress photos and construction updates, please visit our website at https://sites.google.com/astoriak12.org/asd-bond-info/construction-photos?authuser=0

post_text:
ASD Parents and Guardians:

As we prepare for this new and remarkable school year, we wanted to remind parents of a few helpful changes that are happening this year in Astoria School District:

• Astoria School District will be providing all school supplies for students in grades K-12. You will not need to purchase supplies for your student this year!

• Astoria Middle School will not have any student fees, including PE uniform fees, and student planner fees.

• Astoria High School will not have any student fees, including parking fees, sports fees, or any other fees charged in the past.

The decision to provide school supplies and eliminate fees was made before the COVID-19 pandemic and confirmed at the end of June through this years’ school district budget process. We are grateful to have made this decision early, as we feel that it will help our families in their back to school planning and provide equitable access for all students.

When students are allowed to return to school buildings, each student will be provided their own school supplies that will not be shared with other students. These supplies will be sanitized daily while in school.

If students should need school supplies during remote learning, please contact your school’s office and they will help coordinate remote learning school supplies.

Please contact the school your child attends if you have any questions.

post_text:
Students, Families, and Staff,

Astoria School District is gearing up for Remote Learning 2.0!

We appreciate your ongoing patience and support as we weathered the closure of schools last spring and the immediate shift we had to make as a community from in-class to remote learning. We know it was a challenge for students, staff, and families.

We want you to know that we appreciate and we have listened to your feedback. Over the summer, we have learned from you all and have spent the last several weeks and months preparing an improved model of distance learning for the 2020-2021 school year.

We will be releasing more information over the coming days and weeks about ASD Remote Learning 2.0. While we all wish that we could be in our classrooms together again very soon, we are excited to be able to offer an improved Remote Learning system that we believe will lead to higher levels of engagement and learning for our students, and that includes additional supports and user-friendly features for our families.
Attached you will find a brief overview of some of the improvements we are making to our Remote Learning model. We hope that you will participate in our upcoming community forums and will continue to follow the updates on our Facebook page as we continue to work to prepare for the 2020-2021 school year.

DISTRIBUCIÓN GRATUITA AL PÚBLICO DE MÁSCARAS FACIALES EL 25 DE JUNIO

Clatsop County is organizing the distribution of free face masks to the public. The masks will be delivered at no cost to various locations around the county on Thursday, June 25.

2. Hold your fingers to show the number of masks you need
3. Lower your window to receive your bag of masks

post_text:
It was a fun morning at Astoria Middle School. As crews have been working to prepare the classroom wing for remodel, a time capsule was discovered within the front wall. The metal box was sealed and affixed with a metal plate which was sponsored by our local Elks Lodge 180, dated May 22, 1968. This morning, members of the board, leadership team, our local Elks, and construction crew gathered to open the box and discover its content.

Inside the capsule, was a copy of the Daily Astorian which included a cover story updating citizens about Senator Robert Kennedy's upcoming visit scheduled for later in the week; a recording from local radio station KAST, a picture of the then Astoria School District board which included a picture of then Business Manager and long-time school board member, Loren Mathews. Upon seeing this, we reached out to Loran and his wife Corleen, who were excited to get to come over to see the contents as well.

Also in the box, were various artifacts from a number of local community organizations including the Finnish Brotherhood, The City of Astoria, Astoria Area Chamber of Commerce, Astor Column, and Local PTA Organization among others. Once construction is completed, the district will find a way to display the items in the new classroom wing.

Students and Families--WE MISS YOU TERRIBLY!

We couldn't pass up one last chance to see your faces before next school year, so this year district staff will be celebrating the last day of school with a PARADE!

On Wednesday June 10, district staff will participate in a vehicle parade through the streets of Astoria, starting at 2pm (Please see the attached parade route for details) and we would LOVE to see you!

We ask that all families who come out to see the parade practice social distancing, staying at least 6 feet apart, along the parade route and masks are encouraged. For additional safety measures, staff have been asked not to throw anything out of their vehicles to students, or accept items into their vehicles.

We CAN exchange smiles, and waves, and cheers--which we are very excited to trade with you! See you Wednesday!

post_text:
We cannot believe graduation is tomorrow and we get to recognize the Class of 2020!

Although the ceremony is limited to students and their limited guests, you can join us virtually for this event through our live stream through the special graduation site linked here or on our YouTube channel.

https://sites.google.com/astoriak12.org/ahs-graduation-2020/home

Although graduation will look differently this year, there have been many in our community that that worked hard to make it a special and memorable event for our seniors and their families.

We would like to thank everyone in our community for their support on behalf of the Class of 2020. 💜💛 The outpouring of support for our students has been amazing and is so much greater than can be listed here.

💜 Thank you to the staff of Astoria High School and Astoria School district who have been working to make sure our event encompasses aspects of a traditional ceremony blended with a few unique additions we think our students will enjoy.

💛 Thank you to the Astoria Downtown Association, the City of Astoria, Astoria Police Department, the Art students at Astoria High School, and all the businesses downtown who have worked to recognize our seniors through the beautiful window painting and downtown decoration project.

💜 Thank you to those organizations including the AHS Class of 2020 Senior Celebration Committee, the Daily Astorian, Dutch Brothers Astoria, a dedicated and talented group of local sewing enthusiasts, Columbia Screen Printing, and High Life Adventures for your time and generous donations that have allowed us to present each senior with a customized Class of 2020 gift bag upon arrival at the graduation ceremony.

💜 Thank you to Action Sign Works for partnering with our Senior Celebration Committee and district staff which allowed us to distribute Class of 2020 yard signs to each family of one of our seniors.

Again-the thanks we offer go well beyond what we can list here. We are extremely proud of our seniors and to be a part of this community of support.

Congratulations again AHS Class of 2020!! We are proud of you! 🎓💜🎓💛🎓

post_text:
Astoria School District is beginning several facility construction and modernization projects this month. As work progresses in our buildings this summer, the District will continue to communicate with families and community members.

Astor Elementary has already seen many physical changes. You can view Astor’s progress on the homepage of the District website or by using this link: Astor Elementary will see the following exciting changes this summer:
https://sites.google.com/astoriak12.org/asd-bond-info/construction-photos/astor-elementary

• The old gym will become a new multipurpose room that will have the kitchen and cafeteria in it. This should be completed in December, 2020.
• The current kitchen is being changed into a classroom.
• The current cafeteria is being changed into classrooms.
• A new (safer) walkway is being constructed on the east side of the school. The walkway will be the entrance to the building. The demolition work for the walkway is being done by Big River from Astoria.
• The front office is being remodeled.
• New exterior windows are being installed throughout the building.
• The exterior of the building is being painted.
• The special education classroom underneath the gym is relocating, and the space will be changed into an indoor play area
• Astor Elementary will also be getting a new energy efficient boiler system.

Demolition of the Astoria Middle School diamond classrooms wing is scheduled to begin this week. The District will communicate middle school construction progress to families, and post photos to our District website homepage.

We are very excited to see our school buildings transition into healthy and safe spaces for students to learn and grow, and are so appreciative of the support from our families and community members.

Thank You Local Contractors!!!

Construction work is scheduled to begin on Monday, May 4 at Astor Elementary as part of the facility bond the Astoria community approved in 2018. Work to be completed at Astor Elementary includes a new boiler, window replacement, safety systems & security, adding more classrooms, and remodeling of the old gym into a new multipurpose room/cafeteria. Local companies completing the work at Astor Elementary include JP Plumbing, P&L Johnson Mechanical, and Big River Construction. Thank you local contractors for your work at Astor and thank you to the Astoria Community for helping with upgrading our facilities.

post_text:
Dear Students and Parents:

Please help us thank a teacher during Teacher Appreciation week, May 4-8, 2020!

While we often thank our teachers every day, it’s during Teacher Appreciation Week that we like to pause and really show our appreciation for the teachers in our lives. This year, we can’t tell them in person much we appreciate them, but there are many ways to show them you care. A few examples of how you can say THANK YOU:

• Write your teacher a letter.
• Email heartfelt cards, pictures and messages.
• Make a list of the things you love about your teacher.
• Create video messages telling your teacher how much you appreciate them.
• Change your social media profile photo to this graphic
• Post positive statements to celebrate teachers on social media.
• Be creative!

Astoria School District is proud to have over 100 certified staff members that are dedicated to providing the best possible education to students, no matter the circumstances. We are so fortunate to have such a devoted, strong, and experienced teaching staff.

Thank you, certified staff, for all you do for our students and community each day! We see you.

During the April 29, 2020 school board meeting, the Astoria School District Board of Directors adopted a revised 2020-2021 academic calendar. The COVID-19 pandemic and the closure of Oregon schools has dramatically impacted the 2019-2020 school year, which in turn, has affected the 2020 and 2021 bond construction calendar.

The District will begin facility upgrades and construction in May, 2020. Because of the early start to construction, the first day for students for the upcoming 2020-2021 school year is scheduled for Tuesday, September 8, 2020, which is a change from the previously adopted academic calendar.

Astoria School District’s Effort to Support Local Restaurants & Community Members in Need
The Astoria School District's Family Resource Team is connecting with community members in need of essential services, and working to help support our local businesses. The Family Resource Team was assembled to connect our District families impacted by the COVID-19 pandemic with food, services and other resources. The Team has been providing needed support to many local families since the Executive Order was made to close Oregon schools in early March, 2020.
The Family Resource Team would like to find a meaningful way to support our local restaurants while supporting our students and families. As such, we are now accepting funds to purchase gift cards from our local restaurants in order to provide these gift cards to our families in need.
To help support our local restaurants and our community in this manner, please simply make a donation in any dollar amount you wish, to the Astoria School District Office located at the Gray School campus, 785 Alameda Avenue, Astoria, OR, 97103. Donations may be mailed to this address or dropped off at Gray School cafeteria entrance located on the first floor at the southwest corner of the building between the hours of 9:00 AM - 3:00 PM every Monday thru Friday. Checks should be written to Astoria School District 1C, and include “restaurant gift card” on the memo line of the check. If you wish to inform us of a specific local restaurant that you want to support, please list that as well. If contributing a cash donation, please simply state that it should be used for restaurant gift cards. If you have any questions about the Family Resource Team, its function, and/or ways to contribute, please contact Family Resource Team Member, Chelsea Mattingly at cmattingly@astoria.k12.or.us.

post_text:
SUBMISSION OF REMOTE LEARNING SCHOOL WORK
GRADES KINDERGARTEN THROUGH 8TH GRADE

The priorities of the remote learning model in the Astoria School District during school closure include:

• To work to help students stay connected to their teacher and our school community.
• To provide students with engaging and enriching opportunities to continue to think, learn, and grow.
• To support parents and families with resources and support that allow them to support their students’ needs.

In keeping with these priorities, it is the school district’s goal to provide an education for ALL students using an equitable and accessible framework of supports and resources that students and families of all backgrounds, resources, skills and stress levels can access during this school closure.

In grades kindergarten through 8, the District’s focus is that students stay connected with their teachers and that they are provided engaging and enriching learning opportunities. With that being said, numerous students and parents have asked for feedback on the work that students are completing each week at home. We are committed to supporting our students and families and anxious to provide adequate and needed feedback as best we can. As such, we would like to recommend the following options for submission of completed school work:

• Upload work to the enrolled and assigned Google Classroom or in Remind as outlined by the teacher(s).
• Complete the assignment electronically and email or send the document via Remind to the teacher(s).
• For print copies, take a picture of the completed work and email or send via Remind to the teacher(s).

The above three opportunities allow for direct submission of schoolwork to the classroom teacher. For students receiving print copies, if the above options to submit are not available, the school district will be collecting school work from your residence on five separate dates.

If you would like the school work picked up from your home, place the completed school work in the Ziploc bag provided when the homework is distributed, then place outside your home in an easily visible and accessible location. If you do not have the Ziploc provided, use any bag or clip to keep the work together. The District will continue to use proper safety protocols for all delivered and turned in paperwork.

• Collection from your home will be between 8 A.M. and 1:00 P.M. on the following dates:
Monday, April 27, 2020
Monday, May 11, 2020
Tuesday, May 26, 2020
Monday, June 1, 2020
Monday, June 8, 2020

Please make sure your child’s name and teacher name are at the top of the page that is being submitted so we can get the proper assignments to teachers. Once your teacher has received and reviewed your paperwork, they will be in contact using their usual method of communication.

The District is working through a final report card system for grades K-8. Although the report card for the end of the 2nd semester will not look the same as previous semesters in terms of letter grades, the District feels that it is important to provide quality feedback that will support and grow our students in the best possible way during the remote learning time.

You are doing a great job! If there is anything the District can do to help along the way, please reach out to your school office or teacher. Thank you for your continued support.

post_text:
Astoria School District
Student Retrieval of Personal Belongings

With the Governors announcement of the extension of the school closure for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year, Astoria School District staff are in the process of coordinating the pickup of student personal belongings from school buildings. The following is a schedule for personal belongings to be picked up, by school building:

Astor Elementary
For students who attend Astor Elementary, school staff will be contacting parents by phone to verify that their child has personal belongings at school. If a parent receives a phone call about picking up their child’s personal belongings, they may pick up the items on Tuesday, April 21 from 9:00 am to 7:00 pm.

Lewis and Clark Elementary
For students who attend Lewis and Clark Elementary, school staff will be contacting parents by phone to verify that their child has personal belongings at school. If a parent receives a phone call about picking up their child’s personal belongings, they may pick up the items on Tuesday, April 21 from 9:00 am to 7:00 pm.

Astoria Middle School
For students who attend Astoria Middle School, parents can pick up their child’s personal belongings on Wednesday, April 22 from 9:00 am to 7:00 pm.

Astoria High School (Parking Lot)
For students who attend Astoria High School, parents can pick up their child’s personal belongings on Wednesday, April 22 from 9:00 am to 7:00 pm.

Health and Safety Precautions
For health and safety purposes, and in keeping with social distancing guidelines, there will be no public access to school buildings and families should stay in vehicles during pickup. The district has put the following pickup procedure in place:

• Parents will drive up to the front of each school and remain in their vehicles. If possible, please open the trunk of the vehicle. All personal belongings of students have been placed in plastic bags, labeled with the child’s name. School staff will place the bag in the trunk of the vehicle.
• If a parents needs to open the trunk manually they can get out of the vehicle, manually open the trunk, and get back in the vehicle. Once the parent is back in the vehicle, school staff will place the bag with the personal belongings in the vehicle.
• If parents have textbooks or library books to drop off, we ask parents to drop them off in the “book drop box” while waiting for their personal belonging bags to be delivered to their vehicle.
Please respect social distancing at all times, as your health, and the health and safety of parents, students and staff, is our utmost priority.

Personal items not picked up on the dates outlined above will be stored and inaccessible until the beginning of the 2020-2021 school year.

If you have any questions, please call the school where your child attends. Thank you for your continued support

Astoria FFA
April 18 at 4:05 AM ·

Less than 50 Hanging Baskets left! We are so appreciative of all the customers and their patience with this new online process. Here is a few things to note with this years plant sale:

💸Where do I buy/pay?
You can purchase plants online at astoriaffaalumni.square.site
We ask customers to please purchase all plants online with their card. This keeps our help safe and helps track orders better. If you cannot pay with a card, then please email the contact us section or message us on Facebook.

💐 Can I come pick out my own plants?
Sorry, no. These are unprecedented times and it keeps inventory more organized and balanced if all orders can be completed online. We look forward to a more personal sale next year!

⚠️Protocol
ONE customer at a time. If you arrive early and another customer is being helped, please STAY in your vehicle until the customer has left. Plants will be put up in front of the greenhouse or brought out of the greenhouse. Our help has been asked to stand 6’ away from customers as per state and federal guidelines, they will wear a mask & gloves. Customers can grab their plants to take to their vehicles or can request help if needed. No customers are to enter the greenhouse.

🚗 When is Pick-Up?
I know our site keeps saying crazy times! We are working hard to get it figured out. You can pick up two different ways
1) By appointments, email the contact form on our site or message us on Facebook.
2) Open pick-up hours:
April 25th 9:30AM-12:00PM
May 2nd 9:30AM-4:00PM
May 9th 9:30AM- 4:00PM
Time & days may adjust depending on the demand for orders. Please be patient and if you have any questions email or message us.

With the Governors announcement of the extension of the school closure for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year, Astoria School District staff are in the process of coordinating the pickup of student personal belongings from school buildings. The following is a schedule for personal belongings to be picked up, by school building:

Astor Elementary
For students who attend Astor Elementary, school staff will be contacting parents by phone to verify that their child has personal belongings at school. If a parent receives a phone call about picking up their child’s personal belongings, they may pick up the items on Tuesday, April 21 from 9:00 am to 7:00 pm.

Lewis and Clark Elementary
For students who attend Lewis and Clark Elementary, school staff will be contacting parents by phone to verify that their child has personal belongings at school. If a parent receives a phone call about picking up their child’s personal belongings, they may pick up the items on Tuesday, April 21 from 9:00 am to 7:00 pm.

Astoria Middle School
For students who attend Astoria Middle School, parents can pick up their child’s personal belongings on Wednesday, April 22 from 9:00 am to 7:00 pm.

Astoria High School (Parking Lot)
For students who attend Astoria High School, parents can pick up their child’s personal belongings on Wednesday, April 22 from 9:00 am to 7:00 pm.

Health and Safety Precautions
For health and safety purposes, and in keeping with social distancing guidelines, there will be no public access to school buildings and families should stay in vehicles during pickup. The district has put the following pickup procedure in place:

• Parents will drive up to the front of each school and remain in their vehicles. If possible, please open the trunk of the vehicle. All personal belongings of students have been placed in plastic bags, labeled with the child’s name. School staff will place the bag in the trunk of the vehicle.

post_text:
ASD Parents and Guardians:

Tomorrow, April 6th, will be our first delivery of student work packets. A tremendous amount of work has been put into this process in a short period of time. We will be attempting to deliver nearly 750 packets district-wide. Because of this number and changes in request for packets from digital to print, there may be a possibility that your student’s packet isn’t delivered this week. We are working hard to make sure that every student gets what they need to move forward with remote learning. This is a very fluid process right now. Please let your student’s homeroom/advisory teacher know if you did not get your packet or if you would like to change from print materials to digital only.
These packets will be delivered directly to households beginning on April 6, 2020. The following is additional information regarding paper/pencil packet delivery:

• Deliveries will be door-to-door each Monday between 8:00 am and 1:00 pm, beginning April 6, 2020.

• When a packet is delivered to a household, District Staff will be asked to knock on the door or ring the doorbell, set the packet of learning materials on the doorstep, and step back from the door before the door is answered. There will be no personal contact between District staff and families during this time.

• District staff will also have school supplies, including spiral notebooks, pens/pencils, art supplies, paper, and supplied workbooks. At any time students are in need of further school supplies, please email Heather Hummell at hummell@astoria.k12.or.us or call the District Office at 503-325-6441. Ms. Hummell will coordinate the delivery of these supplies.

• Deliveries will not be made to households with NO TRESPASSING or similar signage, or unattended dogs. If you have requested paper/pencil learning and your property has a sign or an unattended dog, please contact Ms. Hummell to coordinate delivery to your home.

post_text:
Astoria School District Families:

Our first priority as a school district is to provide a safe, healthy environment for your children to learn. The novel coronavirus, known as COVID-19, continues to impact Oregon communities and regions across the globe. With that in mind, and following last night’s new directive from Oregon State Governor Kate Brown, we will close Astoria School District schools beginning Monday, March 16 through Tuesday March 31, 2020.
During next week, district staff and administration will be finalizing temporary school closure plans. We will send follow-up communication with additional information about remote learning, support resources, food service, long term educational plans and other updates.
While the school district is closed, Public Health agencies recommend that students stay home as much as possible and avoid larger social gatherings in order to help reduce the potential for transmission. We strongly urge families to follow the guidance from Clatsop County Public Health.
We want to share information regarding the following essential services for students and families:
District Office and the Office of the Superintendent
The Astoria School District Office and Office of the Superintendent will be closed to the public, but available for questions or concerns by phone at 503-325-6441

Breakfast and Lunch Services
Breakfast and lunch will be available for children on all scheduled school days – details to follow

Support Services
We know that closing our schools will have a significant impact on our families and we will continue to work with our community partners to identify support services and resources.
Effective immediately, with the announcement from the Oregon School Activities Association (OSAA), we are cancelling all evening events and extracurricular activities. Please contact the District Office if you have questions.
We will remain in contact with public health officials, elected leaders and fellow school districts, and will keep our website and social media page updated with the most current and available information.
I am very grateful to each and every one of you as we navigate this unprecedented public health situation. I thank you for your support and partnership in this effort. Our strength as a community is our greatest asset.
Thank you,

Craig Hoppes, Superintendent
Astoria School District

Tip off is scheduled for 6 P.M. The #4 ranked Cowapa League Champion Lady Fishermen will be hosting the Lady Tigers of Junction City. The Lady Tigers finished in 2nd place in the Sky Em League and are currently ranked #15 by the O.S.A.A. ranking system. Admission for this contest is $8.00 for adults and $5.00 for students - grades K-12. Only O.S.A.A. approved passes may be used for free admission.

post_text: Astor Elementary would like to thank the Oregon Health Authority in partnership with Providence Health Smiles! Through their dental sealant program, they screened 143 students with 72 students receiving sealants for a value of $6932.49. The dental group found that 22% of the children who were screened were in need of treatment due to active decay, infection, or injury. It was a very successful program with 48% of students returning their permission slips to be screened. We are thankful for the partnership that provides this service.

post_text: Students in Ms. Grothe's class celebrated World Read Aloud Day 2020 early this week! They had many guest readers including Mrs. Patsy Oser, Mr. Tom Wilson, Mayor Bruce Jones, and Park Ranger Cathy Peterson. They also had a visit from Mrs. Lisa Reid, owner of Lucy's Books, and she donated over a dozen books to their classroom library along with some cool bookmarks that were shared with the school library at Lewis and Clark! Thank you to our amazing community volunteers---and keep reading, kids!

UPDATE: 2:45 PM
Students who remained afterschool due to the road closure started loading buses at 2:30 and should be on their way home soon.
Thank you for your patience and flexibility.

Parents,
We were just notified that Highway 30 is closed due to an accident early today. We are in contact with ODOT but are unsure we will be able to get buses through to the east end of Astoria, Emerald Heights, and the John Day area at dismissal time today.

At this time, our plan is to keep students on the following bus routes at school after dismissal time, until the roads are open and our buses can get through:
Route 7 (Astor),
Route 6 (LC, AMS),
Route 13 (AHS only).

Parents who would prefer to pick up their student after school may sign them out at the school. We will continue to update you as we have more information.

THE YOUTH DANCE CLINIC HAS BEEN MOVED TO ASTORIA HIGH SCHOOL.

The Astoria High School Pizazz dance team will hold a youth dance clinic for boys and girls ages 4-14. The clinic is this Saturday, Feb. 8, from 10-11:30 a.m. at Astoria High School with registration at 9:45.
The cost is $20 with a T-shirt or $15 without. Participants will learn a short dance routine taught by the team members and will perform their routine at the AHS basketball game on Friday, Feb. 14.
This is the annual fundraiser for the team's competition season. For more information contact coach Emily Madsen at 503-44-5384

post_text: The nonprofit NW Noggin came to Astoria High School to talk to students about brain science, research, and human behavior. The event was sponsored by the Talent Search program. The group covered topics like addiction, the importance of sleep, and brain anatomy. Students got to hold actual brains, create brain cell models, and see electromagnetic muscle stimulation in action. Thank you NW Noggin!

post_text: The Astoria High School River Bots robotics team began their new season with a FIRST Kickoff on January 4, 2020. Teams from around the country are given a competition theme at the same time and have 6 weeks to build a robot to compete in that challenge. Students learn business and marketing skills, computer coding as well as mechanical and electrical engineering. Having almost tripled in size since its beginning in 2018, the team has spent this week designing the robot and building the chassis. If you are interested in learning more about the program or mentoring, feel free to contact Jessica Todd (jtodd@astoria.k12.or.us).

post_text: The Astoria Middle School "Silver Ocean Robotics" Team is headed to the “FIRST LEGO League” competition in Hillsboro on December 15. They are judged on robot design and functionality and also compete in the project aspect, in which teams highlight an issue in their community and develop a way to fix it. Our team is designing public, waterproof charging stations for Astoria. They have been able to contact Nathan Crater, a city engineer, about their ideas. At the competition, they will present their project to a panel of judges. Lastly, they must demonstrate their understanding of FIRST's core values to the judges. These values include discovery, innovation, impact, inclusion, teamwork, and fun. This team was put together and coached by Rowan Fay as her senior project with the help of AMS librarian Libby Lawrence.

post_text:
Astoria Rotary November Students of the Month

Astoria Rotary honored two Astoria High School students as Astoria Rotary Students of the Month for November at their November 24, 2019 Rotary Meeting. The students honored include Kajsa Jackson and Shrey Sharma. Astoria Rotary will select Rotary Students of the Month during the school year from juniors and seniors from Astoria High School and Knappa High School. To be selected for this award students must be in good standing in school, involved in the community, and involved school activities. Students are also evaluated based on the criteria of the Rotary Four-Way Test which is an ethical guide for Rotarians to use for their personal and professional relationships. This four-way test includes:

• Is it the TRUTH?
• Is it FAIR to all concerned?
• Will it build GOODWILL and BETTER FRIENDSHIPS?
• Will it be BENEFICIAL to all concerned?

Kajsa Jackson is a senior at Astoria High School. Kajsa’s parents are Lynn and Dawn Jackson. Kajsa has maintained a 3.95 GPA while taking most of the Honors and Advanced Placement classes at Astoria High School. Kajsa is a member of the Honors Choir and the Port City Singers at the high school. Kajsa participates in varsity volleyball and basketball and has been involved in musicals and theatre productions at Astoria High School. Kajsa intends to attend Brigham Young University next year and major in creative writing.

Shrey Sharma is a senior at Astoria High School. Shrey’s parents are Sheetal and Sameer Sharma. Shrey maintains a 4.0 GPA from Astoria High School. Shrey has taken all the Honors and Advanced Placement classes at Astoria High School. Shrey is a member of the Spanish Club and the National Honor Society. Shrey most recently was an All-League recipient in soccer and also participates in track and field. Shrey intends to attend a four year university on the West Coast. He plans on majoring in Physics or Biological Sciences.

Astoria Rotary meets on Monday at Noon at the Elks in Astoria.

SCHOOL CLOSURE AND DELAY NOTIFICATION

In case of inclement weather conditions, the Astoria School District will either start school with a 2 or 3-hour delay or completely cancel school. Busses will be delayed for 2 or 3 hours. For example, if your child usually gets picked up at 7:35 am the bus should be at your stop at 9:35 am or 10:35 am.

If the weather does not improve within the 2 or 3-hour delay, the remainder of the school day may be canceled. The decision to have a 2 or 3 hour delay or cancel school will be communicated through Astoria School District’s School Messenger phone system. Each family with an active phone number will receive a call and email so if you miss the call you can listen to the message in your email.

This year, we have also implemented text messaging via the Remind App. Please let the school office know if there have been any changes with your contact information.

If school is canceled, all after school activities are also canceled. The decision to delay or cancel school will apply to every school in the Astoria School District.

Friends,

Last week, we were contacted by the Department of Human Services in hopes that we could connect them with individuals and families who would be willing to open their homes to foster children. We are in desperate need within the county of foster parents for individual children as well as sets of siblings who they are working to place and keep together in the foster care process.

If you would like more information about what fostering a child looks like, or if you know someone who you believe would consider becoming a foster parent, please have them contact our local DHS office at 503-325-9179 ext. 213. They are happy to answer any questions and provide more information on the process.

Thank you for your consideration.

post_text:
On Wednesday, October 30th, Northwest Early Learning Hub invites you to a free showing of the documentary "No Small Matter". This film brings a voice to a topic that gets very little attention, the importance of early care and education. Through poignant stories and surprising humor, the film lays out the overwhelming evidence for the importance of the first five years and reveals how our failure to act on that evidence has resulted in an everyday crisis for American families.

There will be a panel discussion after the film with local Clatsop County leaders concerning how Clatsop County is addressing the issue.

Through poignant stories and surprising humor, the film lays out the overwhelming evidence for the importance of the first five years and reveals how our failure to act on that evidence has resulted in an everyday crisis for American families.

There will be a panel discussion after the film with local Clatsop County leaders concerning how Clatsop County is addressing the issue.

On Saturday, November 2, 2019 at 11:00 a.m., the Astoria School District would like to invite all community members to the grand opening of the newly resurfaced Astoria High School track as a thank you for the support of the November 2018 bond election. The District invites all to stop by to participate in these activities.

Grand Opening: 11:00 a.m.
Junior Track Meet and BBQ: 11:30 a.m.- 1:00 p.m.
United Way Walkathon: 11:15 a.m. - 3:00 p.m.

Students enrolled in agricultural education classes at Astoria High School have the opportunity this week to tour Lewis and Clark Timberland in Klatskanie Fish Hatchery this week. Students have the opportunity to hear from employees including those who are AHS alumni who work in the timber industry. post_text:
Parents and Guardians,

As you are aware, most of the community lost power this morning, including each of the Astoria schools in the District. Please know that when schools do not have power, District representatives work to try to gain as much information as possible about how long the outage will last. I can tell you that all school staff worked very hard throughout the outage to support students as they arrived at school.

Astoria School District is in the final stages of implementing Remind. Remind is a communication platform that helps schools reach students and parents where they are, using text-like messages sent in real time. Once Remind is fully implemented, the plan will be to use Remind during power outages to communicate with parents.
